So in a lot of languages,

01:10:00.160 --> 01:10:03.120
the word that means morally good or spiritually noble

01:10:03.680 --> 01:10:06.880
originally meant noble in the sense of aristocratic,

01:10:06.880 --> 01:10:08.160
the propertied class.

01:10:08.880 --> 01:10:11.280
Like in Buddhism, the Arya Satyani,

01:10:11.280 --> 01:10:13.520
that's Sanskrit for noble truths.

01:10:13.520 --> 01:10:15.440
Arya means noble.

01:10:15.440 --> 01:10:18.320
And Arya is used to mean spiritually noble,

01:10:18.320 --> 01:10:21.440
but earlier it meant the aristocracy, the rich.

01:10:21.440 --> 01:10:22.800
And originally, it was just the name

01:10:22.800 --> 01:10:26.560
that a culture in Northern India gave themselves, the Aryans.

01:10:27.200 --> 01:10:29.440
I'm really working not to get soy sauce on this lace.

01:10:29.440 --> 01:10:32.240
This was later misunderstood by Europeans

01:10:32.240 --> 01:10:35.200
who wrongly thought that Aryan was a race.

01:10:36.880 --> 01:10:38.960
Oops, goddammit.

01:10:38.960 --> 01:10:41.360
Goddammit, kids, can we not?

01:10:41.360 --> 01:10:44.560
Frederick traces the origin of the German word gut,

01:10:44.560 --> 01:10:47.600
or the English good, to the name of the Goths.

01:10:47.600 --> 01:10:49.200
No, not those Goths,

01:10:49.200 --> 01:10:51.680
the Scandinavian people who invaded Europe.

01:10:51.680 --> 01:10:54.800
Frederick calls them the blonde beasts of prey.

01:10:54.800 --> 01:10:58.080
I like to stalk my prey in the small hours of the night.

01:10:59.280 --> 01:11:01.680
The German word schlecht, which means bad,

01:11:01.680 --> 01:11:04.400
is related to schlicht, which means plain,

01:11:04.480 --> 01:11:07.360
simple, originally common, low,

01:11:07.360 --> 01:11:10.000
not aristocratic, not noble.

01:11:10.000 --> 01:11:12.880
So good and bad were originally the values

01:11:12.880 --> 01:11:14.400
of warrior aristocrats,

01:11:14.400 --> 01:11:18.000
who were like Homeric heroes celebrating themselves.

01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:21.760
And Frederick calls their value system master morality,

01:11:21.760 --> 01:11:24.960
this glorification of combat, feasting,

01:11:24.960 --> 01:11:28.720
athleticism, sexual conquest, beauty.

01:11:28.720 --> 01:11:30.400
These things were called good,

01:11:30.960 --> 01:11:33.840
and their opposites, weakness, impotence,

01:11:33.840 --> 01:11:35.840
ugliness, were called bad.

01:11:35.840 --> 01:11:38.240
The ancient nobles worshiped noble gods

01:11:38.240 --> 01:11:40.560
who acted like them and shared their values.

01:11:40.560 --> 01:11:42.560
I mean, if I created a personal goddess,

01:11:42.560 --> 01:11:44.560
I think we all know what animal that would be,

01:11:44.560 --> 01:11:46.960
me and the ancient Egyptians on the same page.

01:11:46.960 --> 01:11:50.320
So for example, Roman warriors could worship Mars,

01:11:50.320 --> 01:11:51.440
the god of war,

01:11:51.440 --> 01:11:53.600
and it was like they were worshiping themselves.

01:11:53.600 --> 01:11:56.400
They were dumb jocks worshiping dumb jock gods.

01:11:56.400 --> 01:11:57.520
Well, good for them,

01:11:57.520 --> 01:12:00.800
but what about the people who got shoved into lockers?

01:12:00.800 --> 01:12:02.800
Well, Frederick's example,

01:12:02.800 --> 01:12:05.520
and this is gonna create some misunderstandings later,

01:12:05.520 --> 01:12:08.400
but his example is the Jews,

01:12:08.400 --> 01:12:11.200
who were colonized by the Romans in Judea.

01:12:11.200 --> 01:12:14.480
And it's certainly not that the Jews didn't try to revolt.

01:12:14.480 --> 01:12:17.520
Oh, they did, multiple times.

01:12:17.520 --> 01:12:18.720
But for several centuries,

01:12:18.720 --> 01:12:20.640
the Romans were just too powerful.

01:12:20.640 --> 01:12:21.840
No one could stop them.

01:12:21.840 --> 01:12:23.120
So the question is,

01:12:23.120 --> 01:12:26.640
what happens psychologically to people who are oppressed

01:12:26.640 --> 01:12:29.360
and who lack the power to overthrow the oppressor?

01:12:29.360 --> 01:12:31.360
Well, in that case,

01:12:31.360 --> 01:12:34.160
frustrated vindictiveness builds over time

01:12:34.160 --> 01:12:36.160
to become this deep bitterness,

01:12:36.160 --> 01:12:38.160
which Nietzsche gave the French name

01:12:38.160 --> 01:12:40.800
Rsentiment, resentment in English.

01:12:40.800 --> 01:12:45.600
Oui, eh, eh, oui, absolument, naturellement.

01:12:45.600 --> 01:12:46.720
I don't speak French,

01:12:46.720 --> 01:12:48.960
I just enjoy making vaguely French noises.

01:12:48.960 --> 01:12:52.720
M'en, pas, quatre, eh, eh oui.

01:12:52.720 --> 01:12:53.520
I don't like the English,

01:12:53.520 --> 01:12:54.960
but I like the French even less.

01:12:54.960 --> 01:12:56.240
Because they're always dressed so well

01:12:56.240 --> 01:12:58.240
and they speak a sexier language than me.

01:12:58.240 --> 01:12:58.880
Stop it.

01:12:58.880 --> 01:13:00.640
This is your final warning, comprendez-vous?

01:13:00.640 --> 01:13:02.080
Good wine though, I'll give them that.

01:13:02.080 --> 01:13:05.600
So there's a German word, Neid, which means envy.

01:13:05.600 --> 01:13:09.360
So why is Frederick using this French term, Rsentiment?

01:13:09.360 --> 01:13:10.800
What's going on, Frederick?

01:13:10.800 --> 01:13:11.920
Why are you speaking French?

01:13:12.640 --> 01:13:13.520
Are you nervous?

01:13:13.520 --> 01:13:14.880
Are you trying to impress me?

01:13:14.880 --> 01:13:16.880
Nietzsche must have said Rsentiment,

01:13:16.880 --> 01:13:19.440
because he thought it was something different than envy.

01:13:19.440 --> 01:13:21.440
I think the difference is resentment,

01:13:21.440 --> 01:13:22.640
and I'm just gonna use the English word

01:13:22.640 --> 01:13:24.000
so I don't sound like an asshole,

01:13:24.000 --> 01:13:28.160
resentment is born not just of wanting what someone has,

01:13:28.160 --> 01:13:32.320
but of a permanent frustration of the desire for revenge.

01:13:32.320 --> 01:13:36.000
It's born of weakness, inability to get revenge.

01:13:36.000 --> 01:13:38.960
Now revenge itself implies weakness,

01:13:38.960 --> 01:13:40.720
at least a temporary weakness.

01:13:40.720 --> 01:13:43.440
We say revenge is best served cold,

01:13:43.440 --> 01:13:46.640
but actually, revenge is only served cold.

01:13:47.360 --> 01:13:49.760
If it's served hot, if someone slaps you

01:13:49.760 --> 01:13:51.440
and you slap them back immediately,

01:13:51.440 --> 01:13:53.920
that's retaliation, not revenge.

01:13:54.880 --> 01:13:56.720
You brought this on yourself.

01:13:56.720 --> 01:13:58.480
Revenge is only a possibility

01:13:58.480 --> 01:14:00.800
when you can't retaliate immediately,

01:14:00.800 --> 01:14:04.000
so you become vindictive, you start plotting and scheming.

01:14:04.000 --> 01:14:06.560
But if you're too weak, too impotent

01:14:06.560 --> 01:14:10.160
to have any hope of revenge, then you become resentful.

01:14:10.160 --> 01:14:11.920
So Nietzsche's argument is that a person

01:14:11.920 --> 01:14:14.560
who's too weak to get material revenge

01:14:14.560 --> 01:14:17.600
can instead get psychological revenge

01:14:17.600 --> 01:14:19.840
by creating a new morality.

01:14:19.840 --> 01:14:21.040
In Frederick's words,

01:14:21.040 --> 01:14:24.320
the beginning of the slave's revolt and morality

01:14:24.320 --> 01:14:27.520
occurs when resentment itself turns creative

01:14:27.520 --> 01:14:29.280
and gives birth to values.

01:14:29.280 --> 01:14:31.760
This is a little high concept for a mukbang, isn't it?

01:14:31.760 --> 01:14:32.800
What are you doing, Frederick?

01:14:32.800 --> 01:14:35.520
So while master morality says that good

01:14:35.520 --> 01:14:38.320
is power, riches, health, and strength,

01:14:38.320 --> 01:14:40.320
and bad is the opposite,

01:14:40.320 --> 01:14:43.040
slave morality, the morality of resentment,

01:14:43.040 --> 01:14:46.000
says blessed are the poor, the meek,

01:14:46.000 --> 01:14:48.080
the sick, the powerless.

01:14:48.080 --> 01:14:50.640
This is the good of slave morality,

01:14:50.640 --> 01:14:52.480
and its opposite is not the bad,

01:14:52.480 --> 01:14:55.040
but a new concept, the evil.

01:14:55.040 --> 01:14:56.320
And what is evil?

01:14:56.320 --> 01:14:59.360
Well, everything that master morality says is good.

01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:04.240
Power, wealth, conquest, sexual satisfaction.

01:15:10.640 --> 01:15:12.320
He's talking about Christianity here,

01:15:12.320 --> 01:15:14.240
he's not talking about Judaism.

01:15:14.240 --> 01:15:16.080
But Frederick thinks of Christianity

01:15:16.080 --> 01:15:20.080
as the spiritual revenge of the Jews against the Romans,

01:15:20.080 --> 01:15:22.640
an inversion of the empire's values.

01:15:22.640 --> 01:15:24.640
But he also thinks that slave morality

01:15:24.640 --> 01:15:26.720
is fundamentally dishonest.

01:15:26.720 --> 01:15:28.720
It's like the fox and the grapes.

01:15:28.720 --> 01:15:30.960
Not being able to take revenge

01:15:30.960 --> 01:15:33.920
is called not wanting to take revenge.

01:15:33.920 --> 01:15:36.400
It might even be called forgiveness.

01:15:36.400 --> 01:15:40.320
Slave morality says that weakness is righteous.

01:15:40.320 --> 01:15:44.080
Submission to people you hate is called obedience.

01:15:44.080 --> 01:15:47.360
Having to wait is called patience.

01:15:47.360 --> 01:15:49.520
Inability to satisfy sexual desire

01:15:49.520 --> 01:15:53.200
is called chastity, purity, and so on.

01:15:53.200 --> 01:15:56.960
And while master morality is born of saying yes to yourself

01:15:56.960 --> 01:16:00.240
as a powerful, noble beast of prey,

01:16:00.880 --> 01:16:04.480
slave morality is born of saying no to the master

01:16:04.480 --> 01:16:06.640
and everything he has that you can't.

01:16:06.640 --> 01:16:08.800
I like to have my belly rubbed.

01:16:08.800 --> 01:16:11.280
Scratch my back above my tail, please.

01:16:11.280 --> 01:16:12.560
I'm gonna put the rest of the fish away

01:16:12.560 --> 01:16:14.320
because it's getting warm and I'm full.

01:16:14.320 --> 01:16:16.080
This has not been a successful mukbang.

01:16:16.080 --> 01:16:17.920
It turns out that it's actually very difficult

01:16:17.920 --> 01:16:19.920
to do a mukbang while talking.

01:16:19.920 --> 01:16:21.520
I should've thought this through a little harder, hmm.

01:16:21.520 --> 01:16:24.960
So slave morality is born of a repressed desire for revenge,

01:16:24.960 --> 01:16:27.920
but that desire for revenge never completely disappears.

01:16:27.920 --> 01:16:29.040
It's there, for example,

01:16:29.040 --> 01:16:31.360
in the Christian idea of the last judgment.

01:16:31.360 --> 01:16:35.200
No need to take revenge against the wicked, my sheep.

01:16:35.200 --> 01:16:36.640
God will do that for us.

01:16:36.640 --> 01:16:41.200
And in the meantime, being weak is good, actually.

01:16:42.080 --> 01:16:44.800
I find this book thrilling to read, honestly,

01:16:44.800 --> 01:16:46.480
and I'm not easily thrilled,

01:16:46.480 --> 01:16:48.640
especially not by philosophers.

01:16:48.640 --> 01:16:50.240
I think this book in particular gets me

01:16:50.240 --> 01:16:52.880
because, especially if you were raised Christian,

01:16:52.880 --> 01:16:55.440
this is so the opposite of everything

01:16:55.440 --> 01:16:56.640
you were ever taught to believe

01:16:56.640 --> 01:16:59.440
that it almost feels, like, dirty.

01:16:59.440 --> 01:17:00.640
Should I be reading this?

01:17:00.640 --> 01:17:01.920
Is this allowed?

01:17:01.920 --> 01:17:03.120
Because even if you're not religious,

01:17:03.680 --> 01:17:06.560
most of us still agree with a lot of Christian morality.

01:17:06.560 --> 01:17:08.240
Like, yeah, Jesus was a good guy.

01:17:09.120 --> 01:17:10.960
Blessed are the meek, sure.

01:17:10.960 --> 01:17:13.120
But then Frederick comes along and he's like,

01:17:13.280 --> 01:17:17.280
mm, morality is just a cope for frustrated vindictiveness.

01:17:17.280 --> 01:17:19.360
And you're like, I need to lie down.

01:17:19.360 --> 01:17:20.640
Where's my smelling salts?

01:17:20.640 --> 01:17:33.680
But wait, there's more.

01:17:33.680 --> 01:17:35.040
This gets even darker.

01:17:35.040 --> 01:17:36.960
Nietzsche thinks that over the last two millennia

01:17:36.960 --> 01:17:40.560
of European history, slave morality has triumphed.

01:17:40.640 --> 01:17:43.200
St. Paul made Christianity marketable,

01:17:43.200 --> 01:17:45.520
the Emperor Constantine converted,

01:17:45.520 --> 01:17:47.120
and by the Middle Ages,

01:17:47.120 --> 01:17:49.840
even kings and aristocrats were kneeling down

01:17:49.840 --> 01:17:53.120
not to powerful warrior gods made in their own image,

01:17:53.120 --> 01:17:54.880
but to a god that was weak,

01:17:55.520 --> 01:17:59.040
suffering, victimized, oppressed.

01:18:00.720 --> 01:18:02.080
So by the 19th century,

01:18:02.080 --> 01:18:05.360
slave morality had become the only morality.

01:18:05.360 --> 01:18:07.440
And it's not just Christianity, either.

01:18:07.440 --> 01:18:09.600
The secular version of these values

01:18:09.600 --> 01:18:12.000
became socialism, anarchism.

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:14.560
About free thinkers and atheists,

01:18:14.560 --> 01:18:16.160
Nietzsche has this to say.

01:18:16.160 --> 01:18:18.720
We loathe the church, not its poison.

01:18:18.720 --> 01:18:22.000
Apart from the church, we too love the poison.

01:18:22.000 --> 01:18:23.280
Okay, the poison.

01:18:24.000 --> 01:18:25.360
What is the poison?

01:18:25.360 --> 01:18:29.440
Well, Frederick thinks that resentment poisons the mind,

01:18:29.440 --> 01:18:32.640
and turns humans against our own natural instincts.

01:18:32.640 --> 01:18:34.080
Not just against aggression,

01:18:34.080 --> 01:18:36.080
but against sexuality,

01:18:36.080 --> 01:18:37.360
against ambition,

01:18:37.360 --> 01:18:38.720
against power,

01:18:38.720 --> 01:18:40.480
against life itself.

01:18:40.480 --> 01:18:42.560
And there's two possible outcomes of this.

01:18:42.560 --> 01:18:46.160
One is that resentment becomes a political movement,

01:18:46.160 --> 01:18:48.560
the conspiracy of those who suffer,

01:18:48.560 --> 01:18:50.320
the tyranny of the herd,

01:18:50.320 --> 01:18:52.720
the revolution that eats itself.

01:18:52.720 --> 01:18:55.440
Only we are good and just, is what they say.

01:18:55.440 --> 01:18:58.160
As though health, success, strength, pride,

01:18:58.160 --> 01:19:01.360
and the feeling of power were in themselves depravities

01:19:01.360 --> 01:19:03.120
for which penance, bitter penance,

01:19:03.120 --> 01:19:04.720
will one day be exacted.

01:19:04.720 --> 01:19:07.520
Among them, we find plenty of vengeance seekers

01:19:07.520 --> 01:19:09.200
disguised as judges,

01:19:09.200 --> 01:19:11.440
with the word justice continually in their mouth

01:19:11.440 --> 01:19:13.040
like poisonous spittle.

01:19:13.040 --> 01:19:16.720
So you get the mentality of a hyper-moralistic resentment mob,

01:19:16.720 --> 01:19:18.480
which I'm sure we're all familiar with.

01:19:18.480 --> 01:19:22.160
The other outcome is that this moralism turns inward,

01:19:22.160 --> 01:19:24.560
and attacks the individual conscience,

01:19:24.560 --> 01:19:28.480
producing asceticism, self-denial, guilt.

01:19:28.480 --> 01:19:30.240
Because slave morality condemns

01:19:30.240 --> 01:19:33.840
not only the external beasts of prey who are oppressing us,

01:19:33.840 --> 01:19:37.040
but also the beast of prey within,

01:19:37.040 --> 01:19:38.880
our own animal instincts,

01:19:38.880 --> 01:19:40.960
what Christianity calls sin.

01:19:41.520 --> 01:19:45.440
So Frederick thinks that modern humans have become sick.

01:19:45.440 --> 01:19:48.160
We hate ourselves, we hate our own nature,

01:19:48.880 --> 01:19:50.640
we hate life itself.

01:19:50.640 --> 01:19:52.720
I mean, is he wrong?

01:19:52.720 --> 01:19:54.160
You see a girl boss winning,

01:19:55.200 --> 01:19:56.800
I only see the will to power.

01:19:57.360 --> 01:20:01.200
Frederick thinks of modern men as once-proud wildcats

01:20:01.200 --> 01:20:03.920
who've become domesticated house pets,

01:20:03.920 --> 01:20:07.120
at the cost of everything great in the human spirit.

01:20:07.760 --> 01:20:10.880
That's very valid, Frederick.

01:20:11.440 --> 01:20:14.800
That's super hecking valid.

01:20:14.800 --> 01:20:17.600
So look, I've been pretty positive about Nietzsche so far,

01:20:17.600 --> 01:20:19.840
but I do have a couple critiques I want to say.

01:20:19.840 --> 01:20:23.280
One is that Frederick associating slave morality

01:20:23.280 --> 01:20:26.000
with the Jews is very irresponsible.

01:20:26.000 --> 01:20:28.240
Even though he didn't intend to be antisemitic,

01:20:28.240 --> 01:20:30.720
and even though he was outspoken against antisemitism

01:20:30.720 --> 01:20:31.600
in his own time,

01:20:31.600 --> 01:20:34.000
when you keep referring to the Christian values

01:20:34.000 --> 01:20:37.760
you're critiquing as Jewish hatred and Jewish revenge,

01:20:38.640 --> 01:20:40.480
some people might get the wrong idea.

01:20:40.480 --> 01:20:42.080
And some people did, Frederick.

01:20:42.080 --> 01:20:44.560
Like your dumbass sister, Elizabeth Nietzsche,

01:20:44.560 --> 01:20:49.040
who became a literal alternative ethno-identitarian.

01:20:49.040 --> 01:20:50.160
God damn it, Liz.

01:20:50.160 --> 01:20:51.760
Kind of goth goals, though.

01:20:51.760 --> 01:20:53.280
Yes, that kind of goth.

01:20:53.280 --> 01:20:54.240
You're right this time.

01:20:54.240 --> 01:20:56.480
My other critique is that it doesn't seem to have occurred

01:20:56.480 --> 01:20:59.760
to Frederick that genuinely caring about other people

01:20:59.840 --> 01:21:00.720
is an option.

01:21:00.720 --> 01:21:02.560
Like not because caring about other people

01:21:02.560 --> 01:21:05.040
is repressing your true selfish nature,

01:21:05.040 --> 01:21:07.280
but just because caring about other people

01:21:07.280 --> 01:21:08.880
is part of your nature.

01:21:08.880 --> 01:21:10.000
And isn't it?

01:21:10.000 --> 01:21:12.960
Isn't caring about other people also in our nature?

01:21:12.960 --> 01:21:15.920
I do think most of what Nietzsche says about resentment

01:21:15.920 --> 01:21:18.720
accurately describes a very real thing.

01:21:18.720 --> 01:21:20.560
But it's not the only thing.

01:21:20.560 --> 01:21:23.440
There is genuine care and love in this world,

01:21:23.440 --> 01:21:24.320
I've been told.

01:21:24.320 --> 01:21:25.440
I've heard rumors.

01:21:25.440 --> 01:21:27.200
And I'm even gonna go so far as to say

01:21:27.200 --> 01:21:29.120
hashtag not all Christians.

01:21:29.120 --> 01:21:30.720
Christ, I'm defending the Christians.

01:21:30.720 --> 01:21:32.240
What is this channel coming to?

01:21:32.240 --> 01:21:34.720
There are Christians, maybe not most,

01:21:34.720 --> 01:21:38.080
but still some, for whom love and forgiveness

01:21:38.080 --> 01:21:40.000
are genuine experiences,

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:42.640
and not just some kind of twisted,

01:21:42.640 --> 01:21:45.360
impotent, passive-aggressive vengeance.

01:21:45.360 --> 01:21:47.920
Where I agree with Nietzsche, and with Freud,

01:21:47.920 --> 01:21:50.720
is I do think a lot of the emotional foundation

01:21:50.720 --> 01:21:54.560
of justice and morality is retribution,

01:21:55.120 --> 01:21:57.840
envy, or some combination of the two.

01:21:57.840 --> 01:22:00.000
But maybe it doesn't have to be that way.

01:22:00.000 --> 01:22:01.920
There's a famous Martin Luther King quote

01:22:01.920 --> 01:22:03.440
responding to Nietzsche.

01:22:03.440 --> 01:22:05.680
What is needed is a realization

01:22:06.320 --> 01:22:10.080
that power without love is reckless and abusive,

01:22:10.080 --> 01:22:13.520
and that love without power is sentimental and anemic.

01:22:14.160 --> 01:22:16.720
Power at its best is love

01:22:17.600 --> 01:22:20.320
implementing the demands of justice,

01:22:20.320 --> 01:22:24.720
and justice at its best is love correcting everything

01:22:24.720 --> 01:22:26.320
that stands against love.

01:22:26.560 --> 01:22:30.000
So Reverend King concedes to Nietzsche

